{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"title","type":"text","text":"# Lifeforce T004 — Creative TRT Hero Images\n\nDedicated concept board for the opt-in **creative image static ad** workflow.\n\n**Stage:** concept selection only. No paid image renders have been generated yet.","x":0,"y":0,"width":720,"height":180,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"latest-direction","type":"text","text":"## Latest Batch Direction\n\n### What is already working\n- TRT is the dominant signal in T004.\n- The winning emotional frame is **feeling like yourself again**, not generic fatigue.\n- Loss aversion beat generic curiosity: **do not skip the overlooked step**.\n- The existing 90-day timeline works because it makes TRT legible without relying on a person.\n- Tony Robbins is an authority layer, but generic Tony urgency is fatigued.\n\n### What these images need to unlock\nUse a thumb-stopping visual metaphor first. Later, compose the approved hero into the existing infographic, educational, comparison, testimonial, or timeline formats.","x":0,"y":240,"width":720,"height":620,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"angle-sheet","type":"text","text":"## Angle Understanding Sheet\n\n### Explain it like you are 10\nA man can train, eat well, and try hard, but still feel like a dimmer version of himself. His doctor may say his number is normal because it is barely inside a broad reference range. Cheap TRT clinics can create a second problem by handing everyone the same answer. Lifeforce starts by measuring more, then a clinician decides what is appropriate.\n\n### Visual territories\n- **The overlooked control:** everything else is optimized, but one important switch was missed.\n- **Identity erosion:** he is still there physically, but does not feel fully present in his own life.\n- **Normal is not optimal:** being allowed through a broad reference-range gate is not the same as performing well.\n- **Stop guessing:** individualized monitoring versus cookie-cutter treatment.\n\n### Source language\n- “I feel like I’m swimming through mud.”\n- “I just want to be myself again.”\n- “They all tell me I’m in range.”\n- “There was a version of you your kids have never met.”\n- “Can’t dial in.”","x":780,"y":240,"width":820,"height":620,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"guardrails","type":"text","text":"## Visual Guardrails\n\n- **No injections, needles, syringes, or vials.**\n- Do not imply TRT is universally indicated or automatically prescribed.\n- Do not imply instant transformation, guaranteed outcomes, or literal de-aging.\n- Keep bodybuilding imagery out. This is about identity, presence, and clinical guidance.\n- A hero can later include an at-home blood draw kit, telehealth screen, dashboard, or lab paper when the composition needs product clarity.\n- Avoid repeating Lifeforce’s existing portrait-with-benefit-circles, generic lab UI, cellular texture, basic timeline, and split-screen before/after visuals.","x":1660,"y":240,"width":620,"height":620,"color":"1"},
		{"id":"concepts-a","type":"text","text":"## Hero Concept Board — 01 to 05\n\n| # | Concept | Visual punchline | Treatment | Product visible? | Source sub-point | Distinctness note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 01 | **The Missed Master Switch** | A premium miniature control room: every small lifestyle toggle is glowing, but one oversized central switch remains dark and untouched. | Cinematic miniature diorama | No | Doing everything right; do not skip the overlooked step | No people, no dashboard, modular for educational layouts |\n| 02 | **Swimming Through Mud** | An otherwise ordinary morning scene, except the man is wading through heavy translucent mud while trying to move through his day. | Surreal documentary photo | No | Exact VoC: “80% of the time I feel like I’m swimming through mud.” | Visceral symptom metaphor without generic couch-fatigue imagery |\n| 03 | **Inside the Normal Gate** | A runner is waved through a narrow grey checkpoint marked only by its architecture, but the bright track and finish line remain far ahead. | Architectural miniature / cinematic 3D | Optional lab paper later | “They all tell me I’m in range”; normal versus optimal | Gives the reference-range reframe a visual world beyond a chart |\n| 04 | **The Missing Reflection** | A man faces a bathroom mirror. His real body is present, but part of his reflection has faded away like wiped fog, leaving an incomplete outline. | Editorial surreal photography | No | “I just want to be myself again.” | Emotional identity image; avoids literal transformation |\n| 05 | **Present, But Not There** | A father sits with his family, but his chair casts an empty-chair-shaped shadow. He is physically present while the visual says he has disappeared from his own life. | Documentary-style surreal photo | No | Family presence; identity erosion; kids have never met the old version | Relationship-compatible without leaning on libido or shame |\n","x":0,"y":940,"width":1120,"height":1020,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"concepts-b","type":"text","text":"## Hero Concept Board — 06 to 10\n\n| # | Concept | Visual punchline | Treatment | Product visible? | Source sub-point | Distinctness note |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 06 | **The Missing Drive Gear** | A pristine high-performance machine has polished surrounding gears turning perfectly, but the central drive gear is absent and the output shaft is still. | Premium realistic 3D | No | Optimized habits but still no drive | Mechanism-support image that can carry infographic labels later |\n| 07 | **The Cookie-Cutter Clinic** | A tactile conveyor line stamps identical male-shaped figures with the same generic treatment box. One figure steps away toward a custom diagnostic map. | Matte 3D / stop-motion clay | Optional dashboard later | Cookie-cutter protocols; 200mg-for-everyone frustration | Competitor contrast without showing medication or injections |\n| 08 | **The Protocol Maze** | A man stands inside a hand-drawn maze of tangled dials, dead ends, and repeating arrows. A single clinically guided path exits the confusion. | Hand-drawn editorial illustration | No | “Can’t dial in”; Reddit protocol confusion | Visually unlike Lifeforce’s prior polished medical-tech statics |\n| 09 | **Dad at Sixty Percent** | A warm tabletop backyard diorama is fully lit except for the father’s miniature zone, where the light is dimmed to roughly sixty percent while his children wait with a ball. | Cinematic miniature diorama | No | Suboptimal Dad; drained and running at 60% | Makes family presence legible without a generic tired-dad photo |\n| 10 | **The Dusty Former Self** | A museum-like glass case holds the objects of his active life: training shoes, a project tool, a kid’s ball, a date-night jacket. Dust covers the case while his reflection looks in. | Editorial still life / surreal 3D | No | Golden-era aspiration; identity loss | Nostalgic and projectable; no de-aging promise |\n","x":1180,"y":940,"width":1120,"height":1020,"color":"5"},
		{"id":"recommended-first-round","type":"text","text":"## Recommended First Render Round\n\n### 01 — The Missed Master Switch\nBest fit for the current winner. It translates “do not skip this step” into one clean image and can drop directly into educational or infographic layouts.\n\n### 04 — The Missing Reflection\nBest identity-loss test. It expresses “feeling like yourself again” without a generic portrait or an exaggerated transformation.\n\n### 07 — The Cookie-Cutter Clinic\nBest expansion angle. It uses the clinic-frustration research and positions Lifeforce as clinician-led without making TRT the automatic answer.\n\n### 09 — Dad at Sixty Percent\nBest persona-specific test. It carries the family-presence direction from T004 while staying visually distinct from normal lifestyle photography.\n\n### Wildcard: 02 — Swimming Through Mud\nMost visceral thumb-stop. Worth testing if the first round should include one image driven by exact VoC rather than the educational frame.","x":0,"y":2040,"width":1120,"height":760,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"composition-routes","type":"text","text":"## Later Composition Routes\n\n| Hero | Static formats it can feed |\n|---|---|\n| 01 — Missed Master Switch | Existing timeline, “do not skip this step,” normal-vs-optimal explainer, Tony authority headline |\n| 03 — Inside the Normal Gate | Reference-range infographic, educational chart, annual-physical comparison |\n| 04 — Missing Reflection | Identity-loss headline static, testimonial, simple quote-led ad |\n| 05 — Present, But Not There | Relationship / fatherhood ad, testimonial, partner-targeted variation |\n| 07 — Cookie-Cutter Clinic | Us-vs-them comparison, 50+ biomarkers explainer, clinician-guidance ad |\n| 09 — Dad at Sixty Percent | Identity arc, family-drive static, simple headline + CTA |\n\nThe hero image is intentionally separate from layout. Once selected, generate image-only candidates first, approve one, then compose the final static.","x":1180,"y":2040,"width":1120,"height":760,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"checkpoint","type":"text","text":"## Checkpoint — Select Heroes Before Rendering\n\nChoose the hero concepts to generate first. Recommended starting set: **01, 04, 07, and 09**, with **02** as the wildcard. After selection, create image-only prompts and generate candidate hero visuals before building any final ad layouts.","x":0,"y":2880,"width":2300,"height":240,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"label-1780278583920","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 01 Missed Master Switch - v1","x":0,"y":3220,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278583920","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 image, premium cinematic miniature diorama with meticulous tactile realism. Show a compact high-performance control room built like a sophisticated physical model, viewed from a slightly elevated three-quarter angle. The lower half of the frame contains a neat bank of many small toggle switches, indicator lamps, and precision dials. Almost every small switch is flipped on and glowing with a restrained warm white light. At the center of the control room, make one oversized master switch visually dominant: larger, heavier, and clearly more consequential than the surrounding controls. It remains flipped off and unlit. The nearby machinery is polished and carefully maintained, but the system output remains dim because the central switch was overlooked. Keep the visual hierarchy simple: the viewer should notice the dark master switch immediately, then understand that all the smaller optimization controls are already on. Use clean cream, brushed metal, charcoal, and restrained teal accents. Place the control room mainly in the lower two thirds, with a calm shadowed wall and soft atmospheric darkness above for natural breathing room. Lighting should be dramatic but legible, with a focused pool of light across the toggles and deep soft shadows. Avoid a futuristic spaceship interface and avoid excessive clutter. No people, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no medical equipment, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":3280,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278583920-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/01-missed-master-switch/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":3280,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278588570","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 02 Swimming Through Mud - v1","x":0,"y":4091,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278588570","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 editorial documentary photograph with an impossible scene presented as if it were real. In an ordinary, refined suburban morning interior, show a relatable healthy-looking man in his late 30s or early 40s trying to walk forward through the hallway toward the day. He wears simple everyday clothes, not gymwear and not business formal. From the floor to just above his knees, the hallway is filled with dense translucent brown-grey mud, thick enough to resist every step. One leg is caught mid-stride and his posture shows effort and frustration rather than theatrical despair. His expression is tired, focused, and recognizable: he is still trying to move forward. Keep the environment minimal: one doorway, soft early morning window light, a distant clean kitchen edge, and a few normal home details. The mud is the only surreal element. Compose him in the lower and middle portions of the frame with a calm pale wall and window-lit upper area for breathing room. Shot on a 35mm documentary lens with natural texture, subtle film grain, believable skin, and no hyper-smooth surfaces. The first-glance read is immediate: daily life feels like wading through mud. No bodybuilding imagery, no dramatic physical transformation, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":4151,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278588571-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/02-swimming-through-mud/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":4151,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278592680","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 03 Inside the Normal Gate - v1","x":0,"y":4962,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278592680","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 cinematic architectural miniature photograph with a clear visual metaphor. Build a refined scale-model running track that begins in a dim grey checkpoint structure in the lower half of the frame and continues toward a bright open track in the distance. A fit but ordinary adult male runner, shown as a realistic miniature figure, has just been waved through the first narrow checkpoint. He is standing only a few steps beyond the gate, looking toward a much longer upward path and a bright finish area far ahead. The gate should feel bureaucratic and minimal: plain concrete, one barrier arm, one small muted indicator light. The rest of the track should feel more expansive, warmer, and more alive. The visual message is that merely being allowed through the first threshold is not the same as reaching a strong performance state. Keep the metaphor readable without words. Use an elevated three-quarter camera angle, crisp miniature depth of field, clean geometry, and natural atmospheric breathing room in the upper portion through open sky and distant track. Do not create a sports-ad victory pose. Do not imply guaranteed transformation. No syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":5022,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278592680-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/03-inside-normal-gate/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":5022,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278596714","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 04 Missing Reflection - v1","x":0,"y":5833,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278596714","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 editorial surreal photograph in a quiet, premium bathroom at early morning. Show a relatable man in his late 30s or early 40s standing at the sink, seen from behind and slightly to one side, looking into a large mirror. His real body is fully present and natural. In the mirror, his reflected figure is incomplete: parts of the reflection have softly faded away as though wiped from fogged glass, leaving a subtle human-shaped absence through the chest and shoulder area. The effect should feel emotionally clear and visually elegant, not horror, not supernatural, and not a before-after transformation. His posture is still and contemplative, with restrained fatigue rather than dramatic sadness. Use soft cool morning light from a side window, warm neutral stone surfaces, believable skin texture, a small amount of film grain, and uncluttered styling. Frame the man and sink in the lower two thirds, leaving calm wall and mirror space above for natural breathing room. The instant read is that he does not fully recognize or feel like himself anymore. No younger version of the man, no muscular transformation, no bodybuilding cues, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":5893,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278596714-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/04-missing-reflection/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":5893,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278600934","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 05 Present But Not There - v1","x":0,"y":6704,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278600934","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 documentary-style surreal family photograph with one impossible but subtle visual element. In a warm, ordinary family room near a backyard door, show a father in his late 30s or early 40s sitting in a simple chair while his children wait nearby with a ball and an unfinished game. The father is physically present, dressed casually, with a tired but caring expression. On the floor beside and behind the chair, his cast shadow should form the unmistakable silhouette of an empty chair rather than his body. Keep the shadow physically believable enough that the visual takes one extra beat to register. The family scene should communicate emotional absence without depicting neglect, hostility, or shame. The children are patient and hopeful, not distressed. Use late afternoon natural light, warm wood, soft neutral fabric, realistic skin, restrained film grain, and a calm uncluttered upper wall for later composition breathing room. Shot on a 50mm editorial documentary lens. The visual punchline is that he is home, but he does not feel fully present in his own life. No medical props, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":6764,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278600934-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/05-present-but-not-there/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":6764,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278606382","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 06 Missing Drive Gear - v1","x":0,"y":7575,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278606382","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 premium realistic 3D render of a precision mechanical system presented as a simple visual metaphor. In the lower two thirds of the frame, show an immaculate high-performance machine assembly with multiple polished gears, bearings, and shafts arranged in a clean readable hierarchy. The surrounding gears are finely engineered, lubricated, and actively turning. At the exact center of the assembly, make one large drive-gear position visibly empty: a precise circular gap with an exposed axle and clear mounting points where the essential gear should be. Because the central gear is missing, the final output shaft remains still despite the surrounding activity. Keep the scene elegant and minimal rather than industrially cluttered. Use brushed steel, dark charcoal, warm cream, and restrained teal accent lighting. Render with dramatic directional studio light and soft shadows against a calm seamless background that becomes darker and quieter in the upper portion for breathing room. The composition should read instantly: many parts are working, but the missing central gear prevents the system from delivering power. No humans, no medical imagery, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":7635,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278606382-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/06-missing-drive-gear/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":7635,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278610486","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 07 Cookie-Cutter Clinic - v1","x":0,"y":8446,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278610486","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 tactile matte 3D stop-motion scene with a handmade claymation feel. In the lower two thirds of the frame, show a simple conveyor belt carrying a line of adult male-shaped clay figurines with slightly different builds, heights, and postures. Above the belt, a chunky mechanical stamping arm repeatedly presses the same plain square package shape onto every figurine, regardless of their differences. The repeated identical treatment should be visually obvious without any text. Near the front of the scene, one figurine has stepped off the conveyor and is walking toward a small custom diagnostic table made from layered map-like cards, varied dials, and a careful branching path. Keep the figures simplified and respectful, not comedic caricatures. Use tactile clay fingerprints, matte surfaces, warm neutral colors, restrained teal accents, and soft studio lighting. Leave a quiet seamless background in the upper portion for breathing room. The first-glance read is an assembly-line answer versus an individualized path. No medication containers, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no pills, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":8506,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278610486-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/07-cookie-cutter-clinic/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":8506,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278614974","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 08 Protocol Maze - v1","x":0,"y":9317,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278614974","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 hand-drawn editorial illustration on warm off-white textured paper. Create a sophisticated but accessible visual metaphor: in the lower and middle portions of the page, a relatable adult man stands inside a maze made from tangled pathways, looping arrows, dead ends, and small abstract control-dial shapes. He is not panicking; he is carefully trying to navigate a confusing system alone. Most paths fold back on themselves. One clean path branches away from the maze and leads toward a simple, calm destination marked only by an organized set of varied diagnostic shapes and a guiding light. Use restrained ink lines with selective muted teal, charcoal, and warm terracotta washes. Keep the upper portion of the paper comparatively open and quiet for natural breathing room. The illustration should feel like a premium editorial magazine image, not a childish cartoon and not an infographic. The instant read is confusion from endless protocol guessing versus a guided route. No anatomical detail, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no pills, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":9377,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278614974-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/08-protocol-maze/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":9377,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278619445","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 09 Dad at Sixty Percent - v1","x":0,"y":10188,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278619445","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 cinematic miniature tabletop diorama photographed with shallow depth of field. Build a warm backyard family scene in the lower two thirds of the frame: two children wait with a ball on a small patch of grass while their father sits nearby, clearly wanting to join them. Most of the diorama is illuminated by warm late-afternoon sunlight. The father's immediate zone is visibly dimmed as though a localized light source has been turned down: his area receives only a muted fraction of the brightness, while the rest of the family world remains warmly lit. Keep the dimming effect physical and legible through light, not through a battery icon, percentage number, or graphic overlay. The father is a relatable miniature adult figure in casual clothes, not an exaggerated sad character. Use handcrafted tabletop materials, realistic miniature landscaping, subtle tactile texture, and a calm softly blurred sky or wall in the upper portion for natural breathing room. The visual punchline is that he is trying to show up for his family while operating with the lights turned down. No bodybuilding imagery, no medical props, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no numbers, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":10248,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278619445-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/09-dad-at-sixty-percent/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":10248,"width":397,"height":711},
		{"id":"label-1780278623832","type":"text","text":"# Creative Image Heroes - 10 Dusty Former Self - v1","x":0,"y":11059,"width":600,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"prompt-1780278623832","type":"text","text":"Vertical 9:16 premium editorial still-life photograph with a subtle surreal emotional layer. In a quiet, museum-like room, show a tall glass display case occupying the lower and middle portions of the frame. Inside the case are a few carefully selected objects from an active, engaged life: well-used training shoes, a simple project tool, a child's ball, and a refined jacket suggesting a night out. A thin believable layer of dust rests on the objects and catches the side light. Outside the glass, include only the partial reflected silhouette of an adult man looking into the case; do not show a younger version of him and do not depict a transformation. The objects should feel paused and inaccessible rather than abandoned forever. Use soft directional window light, restrained warm neutrals, glass reflections, visible film grain, realistic material texture, and a quiet upper wall for natural breathing room. Shot on an 85mm editorial lens. The first-glance read is that an important version of his life has been put behind glass. No bodybuilding imagery, no medical props, no syringes, no needles, no vials, no medication, no text in image, no labels, no logos.\n","x":0,"y":11119,"width":800,"height":711},
		{"id":"file-1780278623832-0","type":"file","file":"Lifeforce/00 Assets/Statics/T004-creative-heroes/10-dusty-former-self/variant-1.png","x":850,"y":11119,"width":397,"height":711}
	],
